metadata.name: Rain Ritual #175
metadata.description:
Every windy gust.... every breeze, gave the restless grasses a chance to spread their suggestive rumours, their spurious gossip. All the while, Old Ones of the field towered above, chanting to their wrathful Sky God for more rain.... Always more rain. 

Instructions 
Intended for high resolutions. Use the following keys once render is complete, to export (letters export without a border) 

Square mode 
   1 (q) : 2048x2048  
   2 (w) : 3072x3072 
   3 (e) : 4096x4096 
   4 (r) : 5120x5120 

Landscape mode (increases spacing between objects to preserve aspect ratio) 
   5 (t) : 2560x1440 
   6 (y) : 3840x2160 
   7 (u) : 5128x2880 
   8 (I) : 7680x4320 

Note: Generated textures are resolution dependant, resulting in very slight differences across resolutions. Composition however, remains identical. 

Browsers 
Tested with Chrome, Edge and Firefox on Windows, Chrome on Mac. 
Note for Firefox users : Ensure "Use hardware acceleration" is ticked ‚Äì Found in Settings / Performance. Other advanced settings to enable include : gfx.canvas.accelerated,  gfx.direct2d.force-enabled and gfx.offscreencanvas.enabled - Unfortunately even with these, Firefox appears slower than other browsers.

metadata.name: rive #787
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns‚Äìand the comfort we find in them‚Äìin slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

metadata.name: Paesaggio #140
metadata.description:
In this work I used the tools I learned in developing precedent works to generate a landscape with hills, flowers, streams, ruins, sky and clouds. The generated landscape gives the impression of a natural one but at the same time it has some "abstract" traits that reveal the geometrical properties of the noise generation process. This noise is used both for the morphological aspect and for colors assignment.

Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[s] to save a 1600x1600 png.


Features:
"Palette": 12 colormap
"Sky":  Day, Night, Gray - 15% Gray, 20% Night, 65% Day
"Ruins": True, False - 33% True
"Streams": True, False - 33% True
"Flower": Red-Blue, Fuchsia-Yellow, Rose-Violet
"Border": True, False - 25% True

metadata.name: The Space Inside #42
metadata.description:
Points fill in shapes on a warped noise field. The resulting images range from soft water colors to distorted, pixelated CRT screens. 

The image is drawn at 3000x3000px and scaled to the browser size. 

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 3000x3000px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

Features:
- Two palette sets
- Light or dark background
- 70% color image, 30% monochrome
- Various combinations of circles and rectangles
- All rectangles 
- 7 types of shapes: random circles, packed circles, checkerboard, orbs, ring, spiral, checkerboard and orbs
- Rectangles snap to a grid
- Fuzzy lines connected groups of drawing points
- Fuzzy lines around the dots
- Bright border on the shapes

Rare

metadata.name: Paper Planes #202
metadata.description:
The joys of childhood are too easily forgotten. Paper Planes is a generative art collection celebrating the joy and magic of origami: from the simplest materials spring delightful forms brimming with ingenuity.

In homage to the handicraft of paper folding, we developed a collection of four pens each with a unique hand-drawn feel: Ink, Pencil, Gel and Dip. They ensure each of our ten origami birds are sketched with subtle imperfections.

Many of the birds are folded from patterned paper based on three traditional Japanese patterns: Seigaiha, K≈çjitsunagi and Shipp≈ç. Other birds are crafted from block coloured paper which provides pop and contrast whilst sometimes birds match their background, accentuating the hand-drawn strokes that sketched them.

A range of layouts bring each mint to life. Birds can flock and fly across the page. They can be confined to a regimented grid or they can escape and embrace the chaos of the currents. Contrasting frames and borders highlight different colours within each of the 15 handcrafted palettes.

If you're feeling mischievous you can press 'C' in live view to ruffle some feathers‚Ä¶

https://www.phaust.art/paper-planes

----------

In live view, press 'S' to save a high resolution download or add '&size=#' to the end of the URL to render at a custom height.

Original artwork by Phaust. Spring 2022. London / Brighton. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Cells - Part 2 #17
WTBS Logo with Fractals #125
metadata.description:
Hard to believe we are going into month 3 of making the podcast! In February we further honed our sound thanks to new microphones and editing, and released our first two artist interview episodes w/ abstractment and MJLindow. Lots more interviews to come!

Thank you to everyone who takes the time to write us kind messages of support. Extra thanks to everyone who helps to grow the show by sharing/retweeting. Extra extra thanks to everyone who supports us through donations and/or collecting our NFT releases.

This project is coded in p5.js with help from abstractment (master of formatting). It is quite a bit different from the first... hopefully you will enjoy the added complexity and variations. There were quite a few discoveries and happy accidents along the way to make it possible. If you are new to coding or otherwise interested in learning, please feel free to browse the code. Effort has been made to explain, as best as possible, how everything works with comments... although this will assume a bit more knowledge than the last.

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #180
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: Shapes #9
metadata.description:
While I was waiting for my turn in a doctor appointment, I saw a 'geometric-ish' framed art hanged in the wall of the waiting room. Those piece was so simple, but in the same time so elegant and this have inspired me a bit. So, I decided to make something similar using javascript, but with the fancy touch of randomization, tks to fxrand() function.

The supply is medium but the price is promotion.
Made with love.

D.
